2 Inputs
The workflow downloads three public files from the SPACER project repository:

the main SPACER dataset;
the comprehender metric file used in the authors’ exploratory analysis;
the speaker metric file used in the authors’ exploratory analysis.

SPACER reports 1056 naturalistic utterance instances and 5808 comprehender responses (Upadhye, Sun, and Levy 2025). The metric files are used here because the present goal is not to rebuild lexical, semantic, phonemic, and surprisal measures. It is to test whether the correction profiles align once those measures are available.

Code
source("R/setup.R")
metrics &lt;- load_spacer_metrics()
A small multiverse exposes reasonable analytic choices. The default version uses fast logistic models without random effects as a screening layer. Variants that change the philosophical conclusion should be refit with the joint mixed model.
Code
variants &lt;- tidyr::crossing(
  phonemic_measure = c("ipa", "edit"),
  include_semantic = c(TRUE, FALSE),
  include_frequency = c(TRUE, FALSE),
  include_surprisal = c(TRUE, FALSE)
) |&gt;
  dplyr::filter(include_semantic | include_frequency | include_surprisal)

fit_variant &lt;- function(phonemic_measure, include_semantic, include_frequency, include_surprisal) {
  dat &lt;- make_process_data(metrics, phonemic_measure = phonemic_measure)
  predictors &lt;- make_predictor_set(
    include_semantic = include_semantic,
    include_phonemic = TRUE,
    include_frequency = include_frequency,
    include_surprisal = include_surprisal,
    include_length = FALSE
  )
  f &lt;- stats::as.formula(
    paste("corrected ~ process * (", paste(predictors, collapse = " + "), ")")
  )
  model &lt;- stats::glm(f, data = dat, family = stats::binomial())
  summary(model)$coefficients |&gt;
    as.data.frame() |&gt;
    tibble::rownames_to_column("term") |&gt;
    dplyr::filter(stringr::str_detect(term, "processspeaker:")) |&gt;
    dplyr::transmute(term, estimate = Estimate, std_error = `Std. Error`)
}

multiverse &lt;- variants |&gt;
  purrr::pmap_dfr(function(...) {
    args &lt;- list(...)
    fit_variant(...) |&gt;
      dplyr::mutate(
        phonemic_measure = args$phonemic_measure,
        include_semantic = args$include_semantic,
        include_frequency = args$include_frequency,
        include_surprisal = args$include_surprisal
      )
  })
